explanation:
To decide whether any operation in OS_SelectSingle is dead (i.e. executed but removable without changing program behaviour) we must know the semantics and side-effects of all checks and calls in the function and the meanings of used constants/types:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro/utility may return, abort, log, or do nothing. If it causes an early return or observable side-effect, removal would change behaviour. Knowing whether it can terminate the call or change program state is essential.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The if-condition and whether subsequent code executes depend entirely on this function's return behavior and side-effects (e.g. whether it always fails/succeeds, whether it modifies global state or the token). If it always returns the same value then the guarded block could be dead.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Paired with GetById; its side-effects (refcount decrement, resource release, observable actions) determine whether the call inside the if-block is necessary. If Release has no effect in practice then it might be dead; if it changes system state its removal would alter behaviour.

- OS_SelectSingle_Impl: The core operation performed when GetById succeeds. Must know whether this call has observable effects (I/O, state changes, timing) or is a no-op in practice — if it has no effect and its return isn't used, it could be dead.

- OS_SUCCESS: The constant/value used in the comparison. Its value and definition determine the branch outcome semantics; e.g. if GetById uses different success codes or OS_SUCCESS is aliased, analysis must use the correct predicate.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type semantics (e.g. contains handles, reference counts, initialization/cleanup requirements) matter because passing &token to functions may produce side-effects; also whether an uninitialized token is used if GetById fails.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM: The parameters supplied to OS_ObjectIdGetById can change its behavior (locking vs. lookup mode, object type). Their definitions may influence whether GetById can succeed and thus whether later code executes.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These internal helpers (invoked by OS_ObjectIdGetById as shown in the call graph) implement lookup, conversions and transaction semantics. Their side-effects determine whether GetById's success/failure and token initialization are meaningful; they are necessary to determine if calls in the target are redundant.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Called by OS_ObjectIdRelease (per call graph). Its semantics determine whether Release performs required cleanup or is effectively a no-op; thus needed to decide if Release is dead.

- OS_printf: Appears in the target's call graph (via macros/stubs). If any of the macros (e.g. OS_CHECK_POINTER) or error paths print diagnostic output, those prints are observable behaviour. Knowing whether prints are emitted is required to determine whether removing code changes program behaviour.

In summary, these symbols provide the control-flow, return-value semantics, and side-effect information needed to decide if any executed operation in OS_SelectSingle can be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e. whether it is dead code).
